<font class="body">
<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseTitle">
		<b>First of Seven Supersessions Address Future of Automotive Technology</b></font></td></tr>
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseSubTitle">
		<b></b></font><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
-->
<tr><td align=left><font class="pressReleaseLocation">
		<b>Las Vegas,NV</b></font></td>
	<td align=right><font class="pressReleaseDate">
		1/6/01</font></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
-->
</table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0 width=80%>
<tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
	<td><font class="pressReleaseBody"><title>First of Seven Supersessions Address Future of Automotive Technology</title>The first of seven supersessions, part of the largest educational program ever at the Consumer Electronics Show (CES), took place today at the 2001 International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology.  The Digital Car Revolution Supersession featured four of the industry’s top executives: David Acton of General Motors/OnStar; Patrick Lavelle of Audiovox Electronics; Jack Withrow of Diamler/Chrysler; and Albert Wong of Clarion Advanced Technology Corp.  Founder and Publisher of The Hansen Report on Automotive Electronics, Paul Hansen, served as moderator.<p>The panelists discussed the impact of today’s technologies on consumers’ lives, as well as possible applications not yet realized by both the original equipment manufacturer (OEM) and aftermarket automotive industries.  Hansen asked the panelists to share their own definitions of the ”digital car” and what consumers can expect to see on the market within the next five years.  All agreed the convergence of easy access to information, safety, entertainment and the Internet is the driving force behind the digital car revolution.  They further agreed that the key to advancing automotive technology lies in the establishment of ”common requirements and standards,” which will ultimately result in more applications, aftermarket installations and lower costs for consumers. <p>With help from attendees, Hansen and the panelists identified a variety of technologies and applications that could explode onto the consumer market within the next five years.  Satellite radio and television, telematics, location based e-commerce, advanced obstacle detection and biometric safety applications for drivers were all included in the list, reinforcing the notion that consumers are not only interested in infotainment for their cars, but increased safety as well.<p>For more information on this conference session or other CES news before, during and after the show, visit www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<p>The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) represents more than 600 U.S. companies involved in the development, manufacturing and distribution of audio, video, mobile electronics, communications, information technology, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services, that are sold through consumer channels.  Combined, these companies account for more than $60 billion in annual sales.<p>CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative advocacy.<p></font></td></tr>



</table>
